WEBVTT

00:00.258 --> 00:03.763
Grace mercy and peace be unto you from our Lord and Savior Jesus Christ.

00:04.444 --> 00:07.549
Again, a portion of the Old Testament reading from Isaiah chapter 42.

00:09.211 --> 00:14.299
Behold my servant whom I uphold my chosen in whom my soul delights.

00:16.222 --> 00:20.428
I have put my spirit upon him and he will bring forth justice to the nations.

00:21.529 --> 00:25.055
He will not cry aloud or lift up his voice or make it heard in the street.

00:25.816 --> 00:30.162
A bruised read he will not break and a faintly burning wick

00:30.722 --> 00:31.663
He will not quench.

00:32.824 --> 00:34.967
He will faithfully bring forth justice.

00:35.087 --> 00:44.457
He will not grow faint or be discouraged till he has established justice in the earth and the coastlands wait for his law.

00:45.799 --> 00:46.940
If you'll join me in a word of prayer.

00:48.983 --> 00:51.646
Lord God Heavenly Father, we gather in your presence this morning.

00:51.706 --> 00:59.154
We give thanks for the witness and the evidence of your kingdom found in the baptism of our Lord Jesus Christ.

00:59.970 --> 01:04.095
that Jesus our King came as one who was also a humble servant.

01:04.756 --> 01:14.487
He willingly was baptized in order that we also might be baptized with the same baptism that we might be named and called children of God.

01:15.668 --> 01:27.442
Lord, we ask that you would lead us to see your son Jesus Christ this morning, his mercy, his grace, his forgiveness, and the ways that he opened to us also the promise of the life that is to come.

01:27.970 --> 01:30.193
We give thanks for these promises we pray in Jesus' name.

01:30.955 --> 01:31.255
Amen.

01:32.417 --> 01:33.218
Congregation may be seated.

01:41.011 --> 01:48.582
Pastor Meisler's not here this morning, so I can talk about him for just a minute.

01:48.602 --> 01:50.105
Actually, I'll just borrow his words.

01:50.586 --> 01:55.954
If you've heard Pastor Meisler pray, one of the things that he's fond of saying and including in his prayers is,

01:56.514 --> 02:01.019
praying to our Lord, Lord, your mercies are new every day.

02:01.060 --> 02:22.866
And truly as we grow as people of faith, as we walk the road of discipleship, that is what we come to learn and know and see and understand in ways that are often surprising, in ways that are sometimes unexpected, often unexpected.

02:23.522 --> 02:43.467
And in ways that are greater certainly than what we could have ever imagined, maybe even as new Christians or new believers or being younger as we walk the road of faith, is that when we cast our eyes upon Jesus, our Lord, when we look to Him, truly we see a picture of a merciful God.

02:45.069 --> 02:49.234
In Jesus Christ, we see the picture of God's love, His mercy, His forgiveness,

02:49.762 --> 02:58.554
His comfort for those of us that walk through this weary world, the ways that he is faithful beyond imagination.

02:59.996 --> 03:19.282
So this morning as we see Jesus come to his own baptism, the beginning of his ministry in this earthly world, in this earthly life that he came into, we see the beginning, we see him as a servant, we see him in his humility coming forth, the beginning of his ministry,

03:19.394 --> 03:21.700
But Isaiah, going back to the Old Testament, paints a picture.

03:22.863 --> 03:36.978
Even before we see Jesus, Isaiah saw him and gave us these glimpses, this picture of who the true king would be.

03:37.602 --> 03:40.446
I'll invite us this morning to reflect on these things for a few minutes.

03:40.506 --> 03:50.099
Truly as Christians, we never grow tired or we should never grow tired of looking to our Lord Jesus Christ, of seeing him and knowing him, of taking in his goodness.

03:51.621 --> 03:54.105
So we can reflect on that this morning.

03:55.366 --> 04:03.838
In Isaiah chapter 42, we find a picture of the great king, the long promised king, the one who was to come and who would rule over the nations.

04:05.340 --> 04:06.802
Isaiah defines him

04:07.330 --> 04:08.151
in this way.

04:09.133 --> 04:12.478
He will not cry aloud or lift up his voice or make it heard in the street.

04:12.818 --> 04:15.923
A bruised reed he will not break and a faintly burning wick.

04:16.324 --> 04:17.285
He will not quench.

04:18.587 --> 04:21.491
He will faithfully bring forth justice.

04:22.393 --> 04:29.183
He will not grow faint or be discouraged till he has established justice in the earth and the coastlands wait for his law.

04:31.306 --> 04:34.611
I'm sure the people in Isaiah's day, this was a nation that was hurting.

04:34.651 --> 04:36.594
This was a nation

04:36.898 --> 04:39.762
people of Israel that were longing for a new day.

04:39.822 --> 04:50.596
They were dealing with very real worldly challenges, foreign armies, foreign nations that were coming in, their own nation being torn apart in various ways.

04:51.076 --> 05:04.594
People who in some other ways had forgotten to follow the ways of the Lord, had forgotten the word of the Lord, had run towards other idols and other things to worship.

05:05.666 --> 05:13.053
So Isaiah comes here in chapter 42 and other chapters of Isaiah and paints this picture for them of the one who was to come.

05:13.113 --> 05:17.738
There would be a day when God would once again do a new thing.

05:17.778 --> 05:22.183
God's servant, God's king would come into the world and he would rule.

05:22.243 --> 05:25.346
He would rule with justice.

05:26.987 --> 05:33.714
And justice in a simple definition of it just means to make things right for all the people.

05:35.010 --> 05:39.454
He would rule with justice and he would make things right for all the people.

05:41.096 --> 05:43.178
And I know the people then longed for justice.

05:43.218 --> 05:58.112
They longed for this idea that God would someday work again when God would speak, when God would act in his creation, when God would set things right and make things new, as it says later on, opening the eyes of the blind, bringing out the prisoners from the dungeon.

05:58.452 --> 06:02.316
What wonderful things to imagine and look forward to and hold on to.

06:04.217 --> 06:04.818
And this

06:05.378 --> 06:08.504
King was to be the servant of the people.

06:08.604 --> 06:10.147
He would bring forth justice.

06:12.872 --> 06:17.881
We wait for justice still in many ways in this life.

06:19.584 --> 06:24.894
We hold on to the truths of what Christ our Lord has already done for us, and yet we know we live in the now and not yet.

06:24.934 --> 06:27.378
So in many ways we can relate to the people in Isaiah's

06:27.650 --> 06:38.100
Prophecy here, the people he was speaking to, where they're looking forward, they're waiting, they're longing for a new and greater day, and this is our prayer also, come quickly, Lord Jesus.

06:39.782 --> 06:48.790
Lord have mercy, because we endure difficult things in this world and in this life.

06:50.532 --> 06:56.658
But again, we cast our eyes to the one who was to come, the one who has come, the one who will come again,

06:56.962 --> 07:00.686
the one we know as Jesus our Lord and we see some things about him here.

07:01.728 --> 07:10.858
Some revelations of his character and what he would do first, he would not be loud and showy in administering his justice.

07:12.120 --> 07:16.325
Verse two says, he will not cry aloud or lift up his voice or make it heard in the street.

07:16.645 --> 07:18.107
So what kind of king will this be?

07:18.127 --> 07:24.114
He will come as a king, but not one who needs to shout, not one who needs

07:25.954 --> 07:28.137
Not one who needs to rule in that way.

07:28.157 --> 07:32.383
Not one who needs to demand that everyone bow down as he passes.

07:32.423 --> 07:49.047
Not everyone who needs to, not one who needs to demand that his voice be heard above all the others, but rather maybe we get the idea that in his greatness, there is also humility in his work.

07:50.589 --> 07:54.354
There is also stillness and quietness.

07:55.490 --> 08:01.078
In his justice, there's also mercy and grace.

08:02.279 --> 08:09.950
He's one who comes as a king, but not as one who would be loud and showy in the ways that might be expected.

08:10.831 --> 08:22.066
Also, he comes and it says, and this one's a little harder for us to figure out what's being said, verse three, a bruised reed he will not break and a faintly burning wick, he will not quench.

08:23.448 --> 08:25.170
What does that mean?

08:25.730 --> 08:36.803
The word bruised is used a number of times in Scripture, and it has a little more emphasis and power than what we might give to it in our English language, to be bruised.

08:37.404 --> 08:43.451
This is a severe thing, and it means actually some damage on the inside, or tearing, or crushing.

08:43.471 --> 08:49.939
Not necessarily an outward mark, but something that has been crushed.

08:49.959 --> 08:52.402
So what's being talked about here, a bruised reed

08:52.674 --> 08:59.500
This is a read that has probably been crushed on the inside, possibly turned over, and the result of that will be, it will never bear fruit.

09:01.762 --> 09:22.642
This can be a stand-in for Israel, for God's people, for a weary world, people that may never own bear fruit, people that may on their own never find the mercy or justice they long for, people who on their own may go searching after all of the other hopes in the world,

09:22.754 --> 09:27.181
but need to know the one true hope of the Almighty God.

09:28.663 --> 09:30.826
And how will he handle this bruised reed?

09:32.649 --> 09:36.335
He will not break it, though it deserves to be broken.

09:36.375 --> 09:38.398
Let's toss it aside.

09:38.438 --> 09:41.543
It's never going to bear fruit, so let's just do away with it.

09:42.244 --> 09:46.350
That's what most to till the ground would do, but not this one.

09:47.532 --> 09:48.393
He will not break it.

09:48.453 --> 09:51.698
And similarly, the faintly burning wick that he finds

09:52.738 --> 09:55.823
He will save and not quench.

09:57.545 --> 09:59.268
He will faithfully bring forth justice.

09:59.308 --> 10:16.114
Maybe we get the idea with this as well, that could it be that there is one who finds the bruised reed and there's one who finds the faintly burning wick, could it be he has power to restore them, to lift them out of the darkness

10:16.482 --> 10:22.948
out of the unfruitfulness, out of the difficulty to raise them up, could there be one who would come in that way?

10:23.008 --> 10:34.800
And verse four, he will not grow faint or be discouraged till he has established justice in the earth.

10:37.162 --> 10:39.104
What good news that is for us.

10:40.826 --> 10:45.330
We grow faint, we grow faint, we become discouraged,

10:46.498 --> 11:01.078
and every king and every ruler, even the good ones, all of those who have come before him, all of those others who would stand in that place of authority and power and attempting to administer justice, everyone, every human person, they all grow faint.

11:01.939 --> 11:03.361
None can rule perfectly.

11:03.401 --> 11:07.606
None can stay the steady course forever.

11:09.649 --> 11:12.593
But the promise here in Isaiah is that there is one.

11:14.496 --> 11:16.178
There is one who never grows faint

11:16.418 --> 11:23.346
who never becomes discouraged, he will establish his justice in the earth.

11:25.348 --> 11:28.572
Now, considering these things, these promises, where do we see them?

11:28.592 --> 11:32.336
I can imagine the people of Isaiah's day thinking, how?

11:33.638 --> 11:40.626
What will this look like, a king who never stops ruling, a king who is so merciful beyond our understanding?

11:40.930 --> 11:45.598
a king who is so faithful, a king who can bring true justice, how can this be?

11:45.718 --> 11:47.040
What does God have in mind?

11:47.080 --> 12:06.994
And I can imagine that they may have trusted in these promises and still not fully understood the grace of God and the work of God and the mercy of God because truly there are aspects of God that are beyond our comprehension, beyond our understanding.

12:09.570 --> 12:19.026
And yet we are privileged to look back and see this one who did come, the one who fulfills these promises.

12:20.066 --> 12:35.329
We see Him in God's Son, Jesus Christ, the one who's seasoned, we just got finished working through as we waited for Him during Advent and in Christmas as we see Him come as an infant, as a child, the promised one, as we see many come to understand what this means.

12:35.389 --> 12:45.805
Now the mercy of God, the love of God has come down, the hope for the world is here and the Magi travel far so that they can get a glimpse of this child as well as they fall down in worship.

12:47.728 --> 12:49.010
And as Jesus grows,

12:49.890 --> 12:53.254
He grows in human ways into his earthly ministry.

12:54.575 --> 13:05.487
His first act is to fall down and bow before the hand of another in the waters of baptism and allow these earthly waters to pour over him.

13:05.547 --> 13:11.073
He is one who comes with justice.

13:12.295 --> 13:19.122
He does administer the law and uphold the law, but he comes with undeniable humility

13:20.002 --> 13:25.090
and mercy and ultimately sacrifice for his people.

13:26.933 --> 13:32.081
And it's amazing, anyway, he's the only king who could ever do this, the only king who could ever fit this mold or uphold these things.

13:33.003 --> 13:38.472
He has complete authority without ever needing to take it from anyone.

13:40.194 --> 13:45.503
He has power without ever needing to crush anyone.

13:46.504 --> 13:47.506
He has might

13:48.066 --> 13:51.572
Without being violent, he grants mercy without letting people off the hook.

13:51.832 --> 13:56.641
He administers justice by grace and sacrifice.

13:59.666 --> 14:02.591
We find the fullness of Jesus character here in his baptism.

14:02.651 --> 14:06.217
He humbly stepped down into this world.

14:06.277 --> 14:08.781
He humbly became baptized, not that he needed.

14:08.822 --> 14:13.810
He had no sin in himself that needed to be washed away, but he became the first.

14:14.850 --> 14:26.102
The first one be baptized so that we also could walk in his baptism so that we know when we are baptized, we are being baptized in his name, in his work, in his power.

14:28.524 --> 14:30.306
And we watch him go through his ministry.

14:30.987 --> 14:34.491
He did rule with justice and with mercy and compassion for his people.

14:34.831 --> 14:37.674
He lifted up the lowly, the prideful.

14:37.694 --> 14:41.618
He brought low so that they also could hear the good news if they were able.

14:44.034 --> 14:45.777
And ultimately, how does his kingdom come?

14:48.401 --> 14:56.333
His kingdom comes as he takes the throne, but not an earthly throne, as we would imagine it, or as we might design it for him.

14:56.353 --> 14:59.658
But he takes the throne, which is the cross.

15:00.239 --> 15:01.340
He becomes broken.

15:01.401 --> 15:03.484
His blood is shed.

15:03.744 --> 15:10.194
The punishment for arson placed on his shoulders so that it might be taken forever.

15:12.194 --> 15:27.189
He is the only one who can rescue us from the weariness of this world, from the plague of sin, of turning against one another, of harming one another, of the things that we do that we know that we shouldn't do and not doing the things that we know that we should do.

15:27.209 --> 15:40.722
He's the only one that can rescue us from this plight and trap and circle of being stuck in the midst of sin and not only that, but death itself, which had,

15:41.250 --> 15:42.151
power over us.

15:45.335 --> 15:46.597
But he did not stay in the grave.

15:48.639 --> 15:50.021
This is how we can know it's true.

15:51.483 --> 15:52.484
He did not stay there.

15:52.584 --> 15:54.286
He did not stay in the tomb.

15:55.427 --> 16:03.017
He was raised again by the power of God, the authority of God, the power of God, the might of God was shown forth in this way that he had victory over death.

16:03.357 --> 16:10.706
The thing that harms us and holds a weight over us, the most in this life and in this world, he conquered.

16:12.386 --> 16:15.290
certainly, absolutely, completely.

16:16.251 --> 16:17.633
And he rose to new life.

16:19.155 --> 16:41.266
And just as in his baptism, as we were buried with him in baptism, in his death, in his resurrection being raised, we also have this promise that rests on each of our shoulders that is given to the people of God, that is given to those, his servants, all those who call upon his name, all of those that he holds in his mercy, he gives this same promise of life.

16:42.946 --> 16:47.112
justice comes now partly, as Isaiah imagined it.

16:47.653 --> 16:51.238
Justice does come now and his name, forgiveness is granted to us.

16:51.558 --> 16:57.868
We live in his mercies, which are new every day, even now, and yet we wait for that last day.

16:57.908 --> 17:10.546
That later day, when we will know for sure, when we will see him face to face, when we will live in his justice and his mercy and his goodness, and while all the tears of this world will fall away,

17:12.130 --> 17:18.479
they will be no more, almost as if they never were, and we will live in his house forever.

17:20.382 --> 17:21.504
This is his promise for us.

17:22.305 --> 17:34.683
Today we see his baptism, we see his mercy, we see his humility, and we are invited today as every day to see the face of our Lord Jesus Christ, the true King, the humble King, the King who ruled by dying.

17:35.905 --> 17:36.186
Amen.

17:37.808 --> 17:39.090
I invite the congregation to stand.

